note.subjective: This is a 28-year old female living in Arizona for the past 6 months.  She is seeking out support to make life changes including changes to her diet and physical activity.  She has been feeling more sluggish and experienced a shift in her mood due to poor health patterns.  In the past, she had been more active and felt that she had more energy.
note.objective: The client has been experiencing exhaustion and a lack of motivation especially after work.
note.assessment: In the past the patient has been more active as an athlete and felt that her mood and outlook on life was more positive.  After long days at work she is struggling to find the motivation to be active.  She explained that when she was a college athlete she felt she did not have a choice but to be active.  Now she struggles to find the personal drive to be active. Her body image has changed since she has gained weight which may contribute to her outlook and mood because she does not like how she looks. She realizes that her nutrition is poor and is willing to change this as well.

note.subjective: Client reports feeling dissatisfied with her current health patterns, specifically her weight and lack of physical activity. She describes feeling sluggish, having low energy, and a shifted mood. She attributes these changes to her recent move to Arizona and her busy work schedule. She expresses a desire to make changes to her diet and physical activity to improve her overall health and well-being.
note.objective: Client appears motivated and engaged in the conversation, but also displays some signs of frustration and disappointment with her current situation. Her speech is clear and coherent, and she maintains good eye contact.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report, it appears that she is experiencing a decline in her physical and mental health since moving to Arizona. Her lack of physical activity and poor diet may be contributing to her low energy, sluggishness, and negative mood. It is also possible that her recent weight gain and body dissatisfaction are affecting her self-confidence and overall outlook on life.
note.plan: Short-term goals include exploring relaxation techniques and addressing specific anxiety triggers. Long-term goals involve improving overall coping strategies, reducing symptoms of depression, and increasing physical activity to improve mood and energy levels. The client will work on identifying and challenging negative self-talk patterns and developing a more positive body image. We will also explore healthy eating habits and meal planning strategies to support her weight loss goals.

note.subjective: Natalie is a 28-year-old who moved to Arizona six months ago. She reports feeling dissatisfied with her current health patterns, particularly her weight and physical activity levels. She notes feeling more sluggish and a shift in her mood, which she attributes to a lack of physical activity and poor diet. Natalie mentions that she was very active in college, playing sports, and had high energy levels and a positive mood during that time. She now feels exhausted after work and struggles to find the motivation to be physically active. Natalie also expresses dissatisfaction with her weight, noting that her clothes have started fitting tighter and she has a more negative outlook on her appearance over the past three to four months.
note.objective: Natalie presented as engaged and open during the session. She appeared tired and mentioned feeling exhausted after work. Her mood was generally low, and she expressed dissatisfaction with her current physical state and energy levels. She was able to articulate her concerns clearly and showed insight into the relationship between her physical activity, diet, and mood.
note.assessment: Based on Natalie's report of low energy, mood shifts, and dissatisfaction with her weight, it appears that her current lifestyle, particularly her lack of physical activity and poor diet, is contributing to her symptoms. Her past experiences with high energy and positive mood during periods of increased physical activity suggest that reintroducing regular exercise and improving her diet could significantly improve her overall well-being and self-confidence.
note.plan: Short-term goals include identifying small, manageable steps to increase physical activity and improve diet. We will discuss specific activities that Natalie enjoys and can incorporate into her daily routine. We will also explore strategies to improve her diet and monitor her progress. Long-term goals include establishing a consistent exercise routine and healthy eating habits to improve energy levels, mood, and self-confidence. We will continue to assess her progress and adjust the plan as needed in future sessions.

note.subjective: The client is a male returning to therapy for a follow up appointment. He reports having some updates for therapist. He reports things are getting better now that he is talking to his mother, cut back on alcohol use and signed up for a Stopping Violence class. The client reports he still has not talked to any of his brothers or sisters since last session; however, client reports he has been in contact with his mom. He says his mom suggested that he go stay with his aunt and uncle. His goal is to get back with his partner and rebuild relationships with his children.
note.objective: The client appears motivated to keep cutting alcohol use. He would like to continue working through alcohol addiction and violence classes to get his family back.
note.assessment: The client appears to be in the action stage of change evident through him cutting back on his alcohol use and signing up for class. He appears internally and externally motivated to continue decreasing alcohol use, attending class and getting back with his partner.
note.plan: The client will follow up with therapist in next session. He will also attend Stopping Violence class.

note.subjective: Client reports feeling okay today, having talked to his mom about his issues with violence, and making an appointment for Stopping Violence. He has also cut down on drinking. He expresses uncertainty about living with his auntie and uncle, but acknowledges that living with his mate in his flat may not be helpful. He finds it difficult to talk about his issue of violence, especially with his mom. He hopes to show that he is a good bloke, a good dad, and serious about changing.
note.objective: Client appears calm and reflective during the session, maintaining good eye contact. He is able to articulate his thoughts and feelings clearly, and shows a willingness to take action towards change.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report of taking steps towards addressing his violence and alcohol issues, and his willingness to seek help and support, it appears that he is motivated to make positive changes in his life. However, he still struggles with feelings of uncertainty and difficulty in discussing his issues, particularly with his mom.
note.plan: Short-term goals include continuing to work on addressing triggers for violence and developing a plan for managing alcohol use. The client will also continue to seek support from his mom and other whānau members. Long-term goals include rebuilding trust with his partner and children, and developing healthier coping strategies. The next session will focus on exploring ways to build trust with his partner and developing a plan for maintaining sobriety.

note.subjective: Ricky reports feeling 'fine' today. He mentioned talking to his mom about his issues, which he described as 'a big deal' and 'terrible' but ultimately positive. He has made an appointment with a Stopping Violence program and has cut down on drinking. Ricky also discussed the possibility of staying with his auntie and uncle instead of his current living situation. He expressed difficulty in talking about his violence towards his partner but is committed to making changes. Ricky has spoken to his partner Kristie about getting back together, but she is not yet convinced.
note.objective: Ricky appeared engaged and cooperative during the session. He demonstrated insight into his issues and showed motivation to make changes, as evidenced by his actions such as talking to his mom and making an appointment with a Stopping Violence program. His affect was appropriate, and he showed no signs of distress or agitation.
note.assessment: Ricky is making progress in addressing his issues with violence and alcohol. His willingness to talk to his mom and make an appointment with a Stopping Violence program indicates a commitment to change. However, he still faces challenges, such as convincing his partner of his sincerity and deciding on a suitable living arrangement. Ricky's self-reported difficulty in discussing his violence suggests ongoing emotional challenges.
note.plan: Short-term goals include continuing to support Ricky in his efforts to reduce alcohol consumption and attend the Stopping Violence program. Encourage him to follow through on his plan to talk to his auntie and uncle about living arrangements. Long-term goals involve helping Ricky rebuild trust with his partner and family, and developing healthier coping mechanisms. Next session will focus on strategies for maintaining sobriety and managing stress.

note.subjective: Client is a single parent.  They recently had an annual exam and there was concern about the amount of smoking and drinking the client has been doing on a daily basis.  Client admits that they need to cut back on smoking.  They have not viewed drinking as an issue.  They drink two drinks per night.  They have also been experiencing stress regarding childcare.  Client's mother has helped with childcare in the past.  They find several things in life as stressful, including finances, work, and childcare.  Smoking and drinking at the end of the day has been client's method of coping.
note.objective: Client has several stressors and has been drinking and smoking at the end of the day as a way to relax.  They struggle with finding childcare for their son.
note.assessment: Client has been utilizing drinking and smoking as a coping technique and reward system.  They have several stressors including financial, childcare, and employment.  Client admits that they should potentially cut down on drinking and smoking.  They believe that having consistent and reliable childcare will help to decrease stress.
note.plan: The client will cut back on drinking alcohol.  They will attempt to limit drinking of alcohol to one drink of alcohol per night.  The client will meet with the social worker in the office regarding potential childcare resources.  They will meet with the therapist in a couple weeks to update on the progress with these two goals.

note.subjective: Client reports feeling stressed and overwhelmed with work, school, and taking care of her 2-year-old son. She feels like she needs a break or reward and has been relying on drinking to unwind. She doesn't think she drinks excessively, but her nurse practitioner has expressed concern. She is worried about giving up drinking because it's one of the few things she enjoys.
note.objective: Client appears anxious and overwhelmed. She has a hectic schedule and is struggling to balance work, school, and childcare. She has been relying on drinking to cope with stress.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report, it appears that she is experiencing significant stress and anxiety related to her multiple responsibilities. Her drinking has increased over time, and she is using it as a way to cope with stress. She is resistant to changing her drinking habits, but is open to exploring other ways to manage stress.
note.plan: Short-term goals: Client will meet with a social worker to explore alternative childcare options. Client will try to cut back on drinking to one drink per night. Client will return for a follow-up session in two weeks to discuss progress. Long-term goals: Client will work on developing healthier coping mechanisms and reducing her reliance on drinking. Client will explore ways to manage stress and anxiety related to work, school, and childcare.

note.subjective: Client Sarah reports feeling stressed due to juggling work as a server, being a single mom to a two-year-old, and going back to school. She mentions using smoking and drinking as coping mechanisms, with her nurse practitioner expressing concern about her alcohol consumption. Sarah reports drinking up to two drinks a day and feels it helps her relax and unwind. She expresses reluctance to cut back on drinking, as it is her primary form of stress relief. Sarah also mentions financial and childcare stressors, with her mother being the primary caregiver but becoming less reliable.
note.objective: Client appeared tired and stressed during the session. She was open about her struggles and concerns but showed resistance to the idea of reducing her alcohol intake. Her speech was coherent, and she maintained eye contact throughout the conversation. No signs of intoxication or withdrawal symptoms were observed.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report of increased stress and her reliance on alcohol for relaxation, Sarah may be at risk for developing alcohol use disorder. Her drinking pattern, while not excessive, is concerning given her stress levels and the potential impact on her responsibilities. The client's reluctance to cut back on drinking indicates a possible dependence on alcohol as a coping mechanism. Financial and childcare stressors are significant contributors to her overall stress.
note.plan: Short-term goals include setting up a meeting with a social worker to explore more reliable and affordable childcare options. Sarah has agreed to try reducing her alcohol intake to one drink per night. Long-term goals involve addressing her overall stress levels and finding healthier coping mechanisms. Follow-up session scheduled in two weeks to assess progress on reducing alcohol intake and outcomes from the meeting with the social worker. Continued support and exploration of additional stress management techniques will be provided.

note.subjective: The cleint was diagnosed with emphysema.  She has been told to quit smoking by her doctors but is unsure on the tools to use to quit.
note.objective: The client indicated feeling criticized by doctors for her smoking despite her diagnosis of emphysema
note.assessment: The client has a desire to quit smoking but feels overwhelmed by the addiction.  She is not sure that she can quit.  She has experience using a breathing apparatus and it seems that it may be helpful using this as a means to measure her improvement with breathing when she quits smoking.  Explored tools that she can use to help her quit, including meditation, exercise, medication, and nicotine replacements, such as nicotine gum.  Discussed her concerns regarding her options including cost and effectiveness.  The client also discussed her concern over her daughter's dislike of her smoking.  It appears to upset the client that her daughter is disapproving.  She uses smoking as a means to cope with stress. She seems to understand that she will have to change her perspective of her breaks to help with the trigger to smoke.  She is thinking about changing how she references to her breaks so that she no longer sees them as a smoke break.
note.plan: Discussed options to help quit smoking but did not decide on how to implement them into a plan yet.

note.subjective: The client reports feeling controlled by smoking, despite knowing the risks and having a neighbor who had to use an oxygen tank. The client mentions feeling a sense of war between the desire to quit and the desire to continue smoking. The client also expresses concern about the social stigma of smoking and the impact it may have on their daughter. The client reports having tried Chantix and mentions interest in meditation and hypnotherapy as potential quit strategies.
note.objective: The client appears motivated to quit smoking, but also seems ambivalent about giving up the habit. The client's speech patterns are rapid and pressured at times, suggesting anxiety or frustration. The client's body language is not explicitly described, but the client's tone and language suggest a sense of resignation and frustration.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report of persistent smoking despite knowledge of the risks, and the client's ambivalence about quitting, it appears that the client may be struggling with nicotine addiction. The client's mention of feeling controlled by smoking and the desire to quit suggests a sense of powerlessness. The client's interest in alternative quit strategies such as meditation and hypnotherapy suggests a willingness to explore new approaches.
note.plan: Short-term goals include exploring alternative quit strategies such as meditation and hypnotherapy, and discussing the potential benefits and drawbacks of nicotine replacement therapy. Long-term goals include reducing or eliminating smoking behavior, improving overall health and well-being, and reducing the financial burden of smoking. The client will be encouraged to continue practicing yoga and meditation, and to explore other relaxation techniques to manage stress and anxiety.

note.subjective: The client reports being diagnosed with emphysema and has been advised by doctors to quit smoking. The client expresses a sense of powerlessness over their smoking habit, describing it as a 'power greater than myself.' They mention having a neighbor who used an oxygen tank due to smoking but were not deterred. The client is concerned about the social stigma and the impact on their daughter. They have tried Chantix and are interested in meditation, yoga, and hypnotherapy as potential aids for quitting. The client also mentions financial concerns related to smoking and quitting aids like nicotine patches and gum.
note.objective: The client appears engaged in the conversation, showing interest in various quitting methods. They laugh occasionally, indicating a level of comfort and openness. The client mentions having a breathing apparatus at home and expresses a willingness to try hypnotherapy and other methods. They describe smoking as a calming effect and a 'little treat,' indicating a strong emotional attachment to the habit.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report of persistent smoking despite medical advice and the presence of emphysema, the client may be experiencing nicotine dependence. The client's interest in meditation, yoga, and hypnotherapy suggests a willingness to explore alternative methods for quitting. The client's concern about the social stigma and the impact on their daughter indicates a strong motivation to quit, despite the emotional attachment to smoking.
note.plan: Short-term goals include exploring hypnotherapy as a potential aid for quitting smoking and discussing the use of Wellbutrin as a medication to assist with quitting. Long-term goals involve developing a comprehensive plan to address the client's nicotine dependence, including exploring financial options for quitting aids and addressing the emotional attachment to smoking. The next session will focus on discussing the client's progress with meditation and yoga, as well as any challenges they face in quitting smoking.

note.subjective: The client returned to this therapy session with a list of their top values.  They shared several of their top chosen values.
note.objective: The client indicated that they are making a shift in their perception of themselves and what they value.  They have a history of putting others first instead of themselves.
note.assessment: The client listed the values important to them including self-respect, inner harmony, health, and achievement.  They explored why these are important to them now and how they work together, for instance, they can't have inner harmony without respecting themselves and putting their needs first.  They have realized that they have put other's needs before their own and that they are suffering because of this.  They have decided that to care for others they have to do that for themselves first.  They are seeing how this change may help them in many areas of their life, such as their career and family relationships.  They also assessed their feelings related to these realizations.  They identified feeling jubilant as a result of these cognitive changes.  It appears that the client is progressing in the area of self-love and compassion.
note.plan: Will continue to encourage the client to live by their values.

note.subjective: The client reports feeling great and jubilant, with a sense of hope and joy. They express a desire to prioritize self-respect and inner harmony, and to break free from the need for external validation. They also mention feeling resentful and angry when they don't prioritize their own needs and desires.
note.objective: The client appears confident and self-assured, with a sense of determination and conviction. They maintain good eye contact and speak clearly and articulately.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report and observable behavior, it appears that they are experiencing a significant shift in their perspective and values. They are recognizing the importance of self-respect and inner harmony, and are taking steps to prioritize their own needs and desires. This shift may be related to a growing awareness of the impact of external validation on their sense of self-worth.
note.plan: Short-term goals include continuing to explore and prioritize self-respect and inner harmony, and to develop strategies for maintaining these values in the face of external pressures. Long-term goals include integrating these values into daily life, and developing a greater sense of autonomy and self-awareness. The next session will focus on exploring ways to maintain self-respect and inner harmony in the face of challenging situations and relationships.

note.subjective: The client reports feeling 'great' and 'good' today. They completed a value clarification exercise and identified self-respect as their top value, which they noted has never been in their top five before. The client attributes this change to recent realizations about consistently putting others first and not considering their own needs. They expressed feelings of sadness upon this realization but also hope and determination to change. The client mentioned feeling jubilant, joyful, and hopeful about this change and noted that it makes them feel like they matter. They also discussed feeling more in touch with themselves and rediscovering their passion for teaching and counseling.
note.objective: The client presented with a positive mood and affect. They were engaged and articulate during the session, showing insight into their recent emotional and behavioral patterns. The client demonstrated a clear understanding of their values and how they impact their life. They appeared hopeful and motivated to make changes.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report of increased self-awareness and a shift in their value system, it appears that they are making significant progress in their personal growth. The client's realization of the importance of self-respect and inner harmony suggests a positive step towards improved self-esteem and emotional well-being. Their ability to identify and articulate their values and the impact of past behaviors on their current emotional state indicates a strong level of insight and motivation for change.
note.plan: Short-term goals include continuing to explore and reinforce the client's newfound values, particularly self-respect and inner harmony. Encourage the client to practice self-care and set boundaries to avoid feeling overwhelmed. Long-term goals involve helping the client develop and maintain a balanced approach to their personal and professional life, ensuring that they prioritize their own needs while also being there for others. Continue to monitor the client's progress and provide support as they implement these changes in their daily life.
